If you play the  @sQ,  RHO will win the  @sK  and force out the  @cA.  Then, when you lose the @d finesse to LHO's King, LHO will take the  @sK  and you will go down one.  The solution is to spurn the @s finesse since you cannot afford to allow the opponents to knock out your @cA before you have set up the @d's.   
Note that when LHO leads the @sJ, it is very unlikely that he has the @sK.   Therefore it costs nothing to reject the finesse.   Your first obligation is to test the @d finesse, so that you can throw off a @c loser.|
